BEGIN_PGML
Infant Tylenol contains 160 mg of acetaminophen in each 5 mL of liquid. If Bao's baby is prescribed 60 mg of acetaminophen, how many milliliters of liquid should he give the baby?

[_]{$answer}{10}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Assume Bao should give [`q`] milliliters of liquid medicine, so we can set up the following proportion:

[```\newcommand{\multiplyleft}[2][\cdot]{{\highlight{{#2#1{}}}}}\newcommand{\divideunder}[2]{\frac{#1}{{\highlight{{#2}}}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&}
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\text{amount of liquid medicine in mL}}{\text{amount of acetaminophen in mg}}\amp=\frac{\text{amount of liquid medicine in mL}}{\text{amount of acetaminophen in mg}}\\
\frac{5\,\text{mL}}{160\,\text{mg}}\amp=\frac{q\,\text{mL}}{60\,\text{mg}}\\
\frac{5}{160}\amp=\frac{q}{60}\\
\multiplyleft{160\cdot 60}\cdot\frac{5}{160}\amp=\multiplyleft{160\cdot 60}\cdot\frac{q}{60}\\
300\amp=160q\\
\divideunder{300}{160}\amp=\divideunder{160q}{160}\\
q\amp=1.875
\end{aligned}
```]

So to give 60 mg of acetaminophen to his baby, Bao should measure out 1.875 mL of the liquid medication.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

